along for the ride.

00:10:10.410 --> 00:10:11.800
And they go around the blade.

00:10:11.800 --> 00:10:15.150
But it's really this is your
control and power.

00:10:15.150 --> 00:10:18.500
But again, really loose
in your hand.

00:10:18.500 --> 00:10:22.020
Not so it flops around,
but it's not tight.

00:10:22.020 --> 00:10:24.651
So there's two ways
of cutting.

00:10:24.651 --> 00:10:28.640
Let me just cut this in half.

00:10:28.640 --> 00:10:31.380
There's two schools
of thought.

00:10:31.380 --> 00:10:34.840
When you're cutting, you're
actually using primarily this

00:10:34.840 --> 00:10:36.420
part-- you guys can
see this, right--

00:10:36.420 --> 00:10:37.480
that part of the blade.

00:10:37.480 --> 00:10:40.130
Basically, the inch and a half,
two inches closest to

00:10:40.130 --> 00:10:40.980
the handle.

00:10:40.980 --> 00:10:45.750
You very seldom use the front
part, because there's so much

00:10:45.750 --> 00:10:46.540
more control, right?

00:10:46.540 --> 00:10:49.160
The fulcrum's so short here,
so there's a control there.

00:10:49.160 --> 00:10:53.840
And the idea of cutting is you
either push the blade away or

00:10:53.840 --> 00:10:55.440
you pull the blade
towards you.

00:10:55.440 --> 00:10:57.480
Both are equally good.

00:10:57.480 --> 00:10:59.780
I'm more of a pusher, because
there's something about

00:10:59.780 --> 00:11:02.300
pulling a blade towards
you I don't like.

00:11:02.300 --> 00:11:03.370
So I like to push it.

00:11:03.370 --> 00:11:06.200
Now, you'll see the
key, of course, is

00:11:06.200 --> 00:11:07.500
not your right hand.

00:11:07.500 --> 00:11:09.080
But it's your left hand.

00:11:09.080 --> 00:11:12.280
Because if you're holding your
zucchini like this, you will

00:11:12.280 --> 00:11:15.290
get your nail, then,
of course, skin.

00:11:15.290 --> 00:11:19.640
So what you do is you
have fingernails.

00:11:19.640 --> 00:11:20.660
And the fingernails--

00:11:20.660 --> 00:11:24.200
that's like an inch away from
the end of my zucchini, right?

00:11:24.200 --> 00:11:27.580
And the blade goes up and
down on my knuckles.

00:11:27.580 --> 00:11:30.010
And that's why we're using
this part of the knife.

00:11:30.010 --> 00:11:32.420
I'm guiding my knife
on my knuckles.

00:11:32.420 --> 00:11:34.480
And that's also why I don't lift
the blade all the way up,

00:11:34.480 --> 00:11:36.100
because then I can
cut my knuckles.

00:11:36.100 --> 00:11:37.660
So by just pushing--

00:11:37.660 --> 00:11:40.790
and when I stop, look how
far I am from it.

00:11:40.790 --> 00:11:43.100
There's no way I'm going to cut
off the tip of my finger.

00:11:43.100 --> 00:11:45.070
And it's also why I don't
have to look, because I

00:11:45.070 --> 00:11:47.070
know I just move back.

00:11:47.070 --> 00:11:48.800
And then eventually you just
keep going like that.

00:11:48.800 --> 00:11:50.510
You just move back and
you never-- agh!

00:11:50.510 --> 00:11:51.270
Just kidding.

00:11:51.270 --> 00:11:53.190
And you never have to look.

00:11:53.190 --> 00:11:54.640
So that's all you have to do.

00:11:54.640 --> 00:11:58.340
And it's actually easy, but
you have to practice.

00:11:58.340 --> 00:11:59.790
It's not something you're
just going to pick up.

00:11:59.790 --> 00:12:01.880
You can't play golf and
squash in one day.

00:12:01.880 --> 00:12:03.103
You have to actually practice.

00:12:03.103 --> 00:12:05.770
And you see people use knives--
whoa my god, amazing.

00:12:05.770 --> 00:12:07.010
I've been cooking
for 25 years.

00:12:07.010 --> 00:12:10.460
I've been sharpening cleavers
with my grandfather for 38

00:12:10.460 --> 00:12:11.430
years, since I was 10.

00:12:11.430 --> 00:12:12.720
So I'm 48 now.

00:12:12.720 --> 00:12:16.410
So I've been around knives.

00:12:16.410 --> 00:12:18.450
But once you learn this
technique, you'll realize,

00:12:18.450 --> 00:12:21.165
wow, I could have a cooking
show too, right?

00:12:21.165 --> 00:12:23.690
It's not that hard.

