And you are Chinese.

00:13:55.990 --> 00:13:58.000
I'm like, OK, good point.

00:13:58.000 --> 00:13:59.530
I'm like, I don't think
it's going to matter.

00:13:59.530 --> 00:14:01.130
It's the best chef wins.

00:14:01.130 --> 00:14:03.770
All I'm saying is, in the
finals, it was Marco Canora

00:14:03.770 --> 00:14:05.210
and Marc Forgione, two New
York Italian chefs.

00:14:05.210 --> 00:14:06.265
I'm not saying it was rigged.

00:14:06.265 --> 00:14:09.230
I'm just saying that's
what it was.

00:14:09.230 --> 00:14:09.850
When someone--

00:14:09.850 --> 00:14:13.680
so Marco Canora in the finale
was cutting bread with a

00:14:13.680 --> 00:14:14.780
serrated knife.

00:14:14.780 --> 00:14:17.570
Not a Kyocera, because
it actually slipped.

00:14:17.570 --> 00:14:20.270
Case in point, it slipped on the
crust and it freaking got

00:14:20.270 --> 00:14:21.520
him, like, [KNIFE SOUND].

00:14:21.520 --> 00:14:22.460
I mean, it was--

00:14:22.460 --> 00:14:24.200
you've seen the movie,
right, "Mary"--

00:14:24.200 --> 00:14:26.230
"A bleeder!" It was
a bleeder, man.

00:14:26.230 --> 00:14:27.560
It was frigging everywhere.

