Let me help you.

00:15:17.280 --> 00:15:20.160
All right, here's a great
tip for bell peppers.

00:15:22.960 --> 00:15:26.460
And buy ones that are perfectly
symmetric, because

00:15:26.460 --> 00:15:27.090
they're easy to do.

00:15:27.090 --> 00:15:29.010
And I'll show you why when
I break this down.

00:15:29.010 --> 00:15:30.490
Sometimes they're all
craggedy and stuff.

00:15:30.490 --> 00:15:31.950
A little bit harder
for this trick.

00:15:31.950 --> 00:15:36.260
So to break a bell pepper down,
I take both ends off.

00:15:36.260 --> 00:15:37.420
And this is still good.

00:15:37.420 --> 00:15:38.200
You can still use it.

00:15:38.200 --> 00:15:39.140
But watch this.

00:15:39.140 --> 00:15:42.330
You take your knife and you put
it on its side to bring--

00:15:42.330 --> 00:15:43.846
can you guys see this?

00:15:43.846 --> 00:15:44.310
Yeah?

00:15:44.310 --> 00:15:46.430
Can you see that here?

00:15:46.430 --> 00:15:46.760
OK.

00:15:46.760 --> 00:15:50.540
So you lay it down and then you
roll your bell pepper with

00:15:50.540 --> 00:15:51.920
your knife flat on the board.

00:15:57.020 --> 00:15:59.340
That's how you break
down a bell pepper.

00:15:59.340 --> 00:16:03.300
And obviously that
would be trash.

00:16:03.300 --> 00:16:05.200
But then if you're doing,
let's say, a stir fry or

00:16:05.200 --> 00:16:09.200
something, you can just cut
it in half, julienne.

00:16:09.200 --> 00:16:12.760
And bell peppers, I tend to put
this way for the knife.

00:16:12.760 --> 00:16:13.545
You could go this way.

00:16:13.545 --> 00:16:15.930
And because these knives are
so sharp, there's no issue.

00:16:15.930 --> 00:16:19.770
It is just easier on your
blade to go this way.

00:16:19.770 --> 00:16:22.890
And just stack and do
julienne like that.

00:16:22.890 --> 00:16:24.140
Easy.

00:16:25.960 --> 00:16:30.760
And that's a great little trick
that you'll use forever.

00:16:30.760 --> 00:16:32.865
And it's not just a trick,
it actually works.

00:16:35.890 --> 00:16:37.180
Mincing an onion--

00:16:37.180 --> 00:16:38.710
hey, these onions are defective,
dude, there's a

00:16:38.710 --> 00:16:41.930
slice in it.

00:16:41.930 --> 00:16:44.710
So onion has peel.

00:16:44.710 --> 00:16:45.960
Take both ends off.

00:16:51.270 --> 00:16:55.390
Now, I find it's easiest to pick
the onion up and just go

00:16:55.390 --> 00:16:58.820
like this across once, because
then you can take your knife

00:16:58.820 --> 00:17:03.720
and you can peel off usually
the first two layers.

00:17:03.720 --> 00:17:07.589
When you take the first two
layers, you're going to lose

00:17:07.589 --> 00:17:10.290
one layer of onion, but you'll
see that in that

00:17:10.290 --> 00:17:12.030
one layer of onion--

00:17:12.030 --> 00:17:14.180
like right here, I don't know
if you can see that well.

00:17:14.180 --> 00:17:15.589
That's the inner layer.

00:17:15.589 --> 00:17:18.690
That one layer's still a little
tough, so that's why

00:17:18.690 --> 00:17:20.862
you only take off that
one inner layer.

00:17:20.862 --> 00:17:23.089
So then you have an onion.

00:17:23.089 --> 00:17:29.450
Now, onion is nature's easiest
thing to mince, because it's

00:17:29.450 --> 00:17:32.000
in layers, right?

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:33.960
Shrek said it, right?

00:17:33.960 --> 00:17:37.230
What was it, life is like
an onion, you peel back?

00:17:37.230 --> 00:17:39.330
You have all these layers.

00:17:39.330 --> 00:17:42.410
You don't cut an onion all the
way through, because an

00:17:42.410 --> 00:17:43.570
onion's attached here.

00:17:43.570 --> 00:17:45.370
So you guys can see
this, right?

00:17:45.370 --> 00:17:47.930
So I'm going to cut, what is
that, like a quarter inch.

00:17:47.930 --> 00:17:51.140
But I'm leaving this little bit
of sliver so this onion

00:17:51.140 --> 00:17:54.000
stays together for me.

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:56.390
And the reason I'm doing that
is if I went all the way

00:17:56.390 --> 00:17:57.980
through, this thing
would fall apart.

00:17:57.980 --> 00:18:01.150
And I'm trying to get a
nice, uniform mince.

00:18:01.150 --> 00:18:03.720
Now, old school-- and you guys
can see this, right--

00:18:03.720 --> 00:18:06.020
old school in France was then
you take your knife and you

00:18:06.020 --> 00:18:08.960
come straight across,
perpendicular.

00:18:08.960 --> 00:18:12.070
The problem with that, and if
you're just learning, and if

00:18:12.070 --> 00:18:15.450
you have a really sharp Kyocera
knife, you go through,

00:18:15.450 --> 00:18:17.110
it can slip and you can
actually lose all your

00:18:17.110 --> 00:18:18.150
fingertips.

00:18:18.150 --> 00:18:19.550
Ouch, right?

00:18:19.550 --> 00:18:21.110
So this is a technique that--

00:18:21.110 --> 00:18:23.360
I don't know if I invented it,
but I use it now because I

00:18:23.360 --> 00:18:24.010
think it's smart.

00:18:24.010 --> 00:18:25.180
I've never seen anyone
else do it.

00:18:25.180 --> 00:18:28.440
I'm actually going in now at
like a 45 degree angle.

00:18:28.440 --> 00:18:32.420
So then if it slips, it goes
into the board, not my finger.

00:18:32.420 --> 00:18:34.790
Now, a French chef
would be like,

00:18:34.790 --> 00:18:35.910
it's not perfect [FRENCH].

00:18:35.910 --> 00:18:35.940
It's not.

00:18:35.940 --> 00:18:37.200
It's not a perfect square.

00:18:37.200 --> 00:18:39.570
Now, you can imagine the sides
are at 45 degrees.

00:18:39.570 --> 00:18:41.680
But is that going to affect the
way the risotto tastes or

00:18:41.680 --> 00:18:42.360
the stir fry tastes?

00:18:42.360 --> 00:18:43.850
Of course not.

00:18:43.850 --> 00:18:44.990
It actually--

00:18:44.990 --> 00:18:49.350
if I think I remember my
physics, I'm creating more

00:18:49.350 --> 00:18:51.750
surface area now so it's
actually better for flavor.

00:18:51.750 --> 00:18:55.040
I'm going to use that.

00:18:55.040 --> 00:18:57.370
But I do this because
it's just safer.

00:18:57.370 --> 00:18:59.710
So you come across this way.

00:18:59.710 --> 00:19:01.620
And then once you get
here, then you

00:19:01.620 --> 00:19:03.580
just go straight down.

00:19:03.580 --> 00:19:07.740
And when you do that, you get
perfectly minced onions.

00:19:07.740 --> 00:19:09.400
So again, this is not
a technique--

00:19:09.400 --> 00:19:10.760
and people always say, well,
what do you do at the end?

00:19:10.760 --> 00:19:12.060
So this is still minced.

00:19:12.060 --> 00:19:14.200
This one is still
minced, right?

00:19:14.200 --> 00:19:16.520
Now, when I get to
this end, that's

00:19:16.520 --> 00:19:17.810
the end that's attached.

00:19:17.810 --> 00:19:20.170
So I usually just do one more
slice and I just turn it on

00:19:20.170 --> 00:19:23.220
its side and then just
go through it.

00:19:23.220 --> 00:19:24.760
Again, this is cooking
at home, guys.

00:19:24.760 --> 00:19:26.780
No one's going to be like, your
dinner was great, but

00:19:26.780 --> 00:19:29.845
your onions were un-uniform
at the end.

00:19:29.845 --> 00:19:31.190
You can tell them to go--

00:19:31.190 --> 00:19:32.890
you know.

00:19:32.890 --> 00:19:37.180
The key is just gentle
control.

00:19:37.180 --> 00:19:38.260
That's the key.

00:19:38.260 --> 00:19:40.780
And by the way, it does
work if you're

00:19:40.780 --> 00:19:43.400
left-handed, obviously.

00:19:43.400 --> 00:19:44.950
There are knives, though,
in Japan--

00:19:44.950 --> 00:19:47.490
the sashimi knives are
one-sided, and you're

00:19:47.490 --> 00:19:48.020
basically--

00:19:48.020 --> 00:19:50.000
you are SOL if you're
left-handed.

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:55.520
Because you can't cut this way
because it's forged that way.

