00:26:01.240 --> 00:26:07.960
I think people get scared
when they cook scallops

00:26:07.960 --> 00:26:09.285
and fish in a pan.

00:26:09.285 --> 00:26:11.170
They think they have to
use nonstick pans

00:26:11.170 --> 00:26:12.660
so it doesn't stick.

00:26:12.660 --> 00:26:13.785
That's not true.

00:26:13.785 --> 00:26:16.350
And again, in one of these
videos, I show you

00:26:16.350 --> 00:26:17.760
how you sear fish.

00:26:17.760 --> 00:26:19.230
Get a good pan.

00:26:19.230 --> 00:26:20.640
That's key.

00:26:20.640 --> 00:26:23.560
Did my voice just break?

00:26:23.560 --> 00:26:26.790
It's that time of the year.

00:26:26.790 --> 00:26:29.130
All-Clad is my favorite, because
they're thick and

00:26:29.130 --> 00:26:30.230
they're three-ply.

00:26:30.230 --> 00:26:31.620
And they have aluminum.

00:26:31.620 --> 00:26:34.280
The expensive ones have copper
inside, but this is aluminum.

00:26:34.280 --> 00:26:36.250
I'm talking about the
interior, right?

00:26:36.250 --> 00:26:38.550
And it conducts heat
really well.

00:26:38.550 --> 00:26:41.830
So in those pans, not in
nonstick, you make sure you

00:26:41.830 --> 00:26:47.440
pre-heat on medium-high heat
for a minute or so.

00:26:47.440 --> 00:26:50.110
When you add the oil-- and
I use Canola oil--

00:26:50.110 --> 00:26:53.390
the oil should dance, meaning it
should hit the pan and kind

00:26:53.390 --> 00:26:54.740
of move around.

00:26:54.740 --> 00:26:57.120
If it smokes, it's
a little too hot.

00:26:57.120 --> 00:26:57.700
Don't panic.

00:26:57.700 --> 00:27:01.090
If it actually start smoking
a lot, add a lot of oil.

00:27:01.090 --> 00:27:02.070
Seriously.

00:27:02.070 --> 00:27:03.750
And that will cool
the pan down.

00:27:03.750 --> 00:27:06.150
Then dump that oil into
a stainless steel pan.

00:27:06.150 --> 00:27:09.050
It's still good, it just
helped cool it off.

00:27:09.050 --> 00:27:11.980
Don't panic and add water
or something stupid.

00:27:11.980 --> 00:27:15.340
That would be, ding, not good.

00:27:15.340 --> 00:27:18.420
But the oil should dance.

00:27:18.420 --> 00:27:21.910
And when you add the oil to a
hot pan, your seasoned piece

00:27:21.910 --> 00:27:24.480
of salmon or scallops, when you
add it to the pan, will

00:27:24.480 --> 00:27:26.230
not stick at all.

00:27:26.230 --> 00:27:28.520
It's when you add salmon or
scallops or something to a pan

00:27:28.520 --> 00:27:31.960
that's cold and you add oil to
the cold pan and then heat it

00:27:31.960 --> 00:27:33.610
up, it's not the same thing.

00:27:33.610 --> 00:27:35.480
Because the oil changes
its properties when

00:27:35.480 --> 00:27:36.910
it hits a hot pan.

00:27:36.910 --> 00:27:39.330
And it's much more viscous.

00:27:39.330 --> 00:27:41.120
It does stick--

00:27:41.120 --> 00:27:43.610
and this is the same for all you
guys that like to grill--

00:27:43.610 --> 00:27:46.085
don't do the rookie move
and try to see if

00:27:46.085 --> 00:27:47.120
its stuck or not.

00:27:47.120 --> 00:27:48.810
You can tell if its stuck.

00:27:48.810 --> 00:27:50.190
Don't try to un-stick it,
because you're just

00:27:50.190 --> 00:27:51.950
going to rip it.

00:27:51.950 --> 00:27:53.540
Let it sit there.

00:27:53.540 --> 00:27:54.420
Let it cook.

00:27:54.420 --> 00:27:55.760
Let it crisp up.

00:27:55.760 --> 00:27:59.490
It will un-stick itself, on
the grill or in a pan.

00:27:59.490 --> 00:28:01.720
You might have to take
a little bit effort.

00:28:01.720 --> 00:28:03.840
But to be honest in a restaurant
when we're cooking

00:28:03.840 --> 00:28:07.110
fish and scallops, it's 70%
cooked on one side.

00:28:07.110 --> 00:28:08.930
And you kind of flip it on the
other side and it's gone.

00:28:08.930 --> 00:28:10.000
It's not 50-50.

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:13.490
So it's OK that that one side
gets that nice, brown, almost

00:28:13.490 --> 00:28:15.450
crunchy caramelized flavor.

00:28:15.450 --> 00:28:16.290
Especially scallops.

00:28:16.290 --> 00:28:18.615
I use that as an example because
those will shred.

00:28:18.615 --> 00:28:21.380
If you try to un-stick a
scallop, especially the

00:28:21.380 --> 00:28:24.450
dayboats and the Taylor Bays,
the small ones, if the pan's

00:28:24.450 --> 00:28:27.270
no good, it's going
to just shred up.

00:28:27.270 --> 00:28:30.065
Non-sticks are fine, but you
can't get good caramelization

00:28:30.065 --> 00:28:31.120
with a nonstick.

00:28:31.120 --> 00:28:32.770
So I like real pans.

00:28:32.770 --> 00:28:33.720
Woks, I love too.

00:28:33.720 --> 00:28:37.610
One of my favorite tools or
appliances at home is a cast

00:28:37.610 --> 00:28:42.000
iron wok, this big red
one made by Creuset.

00:28:42.000 --> 00:28:43.070
And it's thick.

00:28:43.070 --> 00:28:45.470
Because we have a Wolf range,
which is a great range.

00:28:45.470 --> 00:28:48.350
But the burner's 20,000 BTUs.

00:28:48.350 --> 00:28:52.090
My wok burners at Blue Ginger
are 80,000 BTUs apiece.

00:28:52.090 --> 00:28:54.150
So that heat is so intense,
nothing is

00:28:54.150 --> 00:28:54.910
ever going to stick.

00:28:54.910 --> 00:28:59.410
But to generate that heat at
home, if you use an All-Clad

00:28:59.410 --> 00:29:00.000
wok is good.

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:02.100
But Creusets are even
thicker, so they can

00:29:02.100 --> 00:29:03.710
really get super hot.

00:29:03.710 --> 00:29:07.010
And the other tip is make sure
your wok doesn't have the wood

00:29:07.010 --> 00:29:07.950
handle or plastic handle.

00:29:07.950 --> 00:29:10.630
Make sure it's stainless steel
all the way, because the trick

00:29:10.630 --> 00:29:13.660
you have is you put it into your
oven at 550 degrees for

00:29:13.660 --> 00:29:16.270
10 minutes to preheat the wok.

00:29:16.270 --> 00:29:19.410
Then take it out-- obviously
with a towel.

00:29:19.410 --> 00:29:22.040
Obviously, leave the towel on
the handle, because someone's

00:29:22.040 --> 00:29:23.870
going to come over
and grab it.

00:29:23.870 --> 00:29:26.070
In France, they put flour
on the handle.

00:29:26.070 --> 00:29:27.670
And I was in France the
first time like,

00:29:27.670 --> 00:29:29.500
Chef, what's that for?

00:29:29.500 --> 00:29:30.450
I burned the crap out--

00:29:30.450 --> 00:29:32.300
It would've been nice if he
told me, but there's a

00:29:32.300 --> 00:29:33.580
learning curve.

00:29:33.580 --> 00:29:39.820
They have those great suede
kind of slip-on things.

00:29:39.820 --> 00:29:40.960
And you put it on the handle.

00:29:40.960 --> 00:29:42.860
Those are the best, because
they won't fall off.

00:29:42.860 --> 00:29:45.800
But once you pre-heat it at 550,
then you could put it on

00:29:45.800 --> 00:29:46.560
your hot flame.

00:29:46.560 --> 00:29:49.850
That flame will keep that
wok screeching hot.

00:29:49.850 --> 00:29:53.520
So that "ch" sound you get when
you wok stir, you want to

00:29:53.520 --> 00:29:54.880
always maintain.

00:29:54.880 --> 00:29:57.010
Quite often in a lot of recipe
books when you put in the

00:29:57.010 --> 00:29:59.120
whole recipe, [FIZZLING SOUND].

00:29:59.120 --> 00:30:00.430
Then you're braising.

00:30:00.430 --> 00:30:02.650
It still will taste good, but
you're not going to get

00:30:02.650 --> 00:30:04.500
everything that wok stirring
is great, which keeps

00:30:04.500 --> 00:30:06.730
vegetables crisp and seals
in the flavor of

00:30:06.730 --> 00:30:07.580
the meat and whatnot.

00:30:07.580 --> 00:30:09.920
So you want to keep
that "ch" sound.

00:30:09.920 --> 00:30:11.860
And by the way, I kind
of wish I had a pan,

00:30:11.860 --> 00:30:14.190
but flipping food--

00:30:14.190 --> 00:30:15.510
easy.

00:30:15.510 --> 00:30:18.430
Really easy, but practice,
just like cutting.

00:30:18.430 --> 00:30:21.590
You have to actually take dried
rice or dried beans,

00:30:21.590 --> 00:30:22.940
frijoles, and put them--

00:30:22.940 --> 00:30:23.990
a cup.

00:30:23.990 --> 00:30:26.860
And all you do-- and I don't
have a pan, but all you do--

00:30:26.860 --> 00:30:27.650
and you'll do this.

00:30:27.650 --> 00:30:29.340
Go to your back yard, where
no one's watching you.

00:30:29.340 --> 00:30:30.960
Don't do it here in front
of your peers, or

00:30:30.960 --> 00:30:32.020
you'll spill it.

00:30:32.020 --> 00:30:34.220
Just pull the pan, but at the
very last moment you pull, you

00:30:34.220 --> 00:30:36.650
just flip the front
edge towards you.

00:30:36.650 --> 00:30:38.920
Within one minute, you'll
be flipping

00:30:38.920 --> 00:30:40.730
your food in a cascade.

00:30:40.730 --> 00:30:42.260
And we do that not
to show off.

00:30:42.260 --> 00:30:44.900
We do that because in a real
kitchen, we don't have places

00:30:44.900 --> 00:30:48.020
to put tongs and spoons
and stuff.

00:30:48.020 --> 00:30:50.130
And we're using both hands
to quickly mix stuff.

00:30:50.130 --> 00:30:52.920
It mixes stuff better and it
also doesn't break stuff up

00:30:52.920 --> 00:30:54.230
like a spoon and tongs would.

00:30:54.230 --> 00:30:57.070
So there's a reason we
flip food this way.

00:30:57.070 --> 00:30:58.700
But it's a great technique.

00:30:58.700 --> 00:31:01.630
And again, I show
it in the book.

00:31:01.630 --> 00:31:02.770
It's a great technique.

00:31:02.770 --> 00:31:05.170
Again, don't grab the pan like
this, it'll go everywhere.

00:31:05.170 --> 00:31:07.200
Is very--

00:31:07.200 --> 00:31:08.250
it's like almost everything.

00:31:08.250 --> 00:31:11.200
Do it softly, in a way.

00:31:11.200 --> 00:31:12.740
I mean, when you hit a keyboard
hard, you're not

00:31:12.740 --> 00:31:14.001
typing any faster, right?

00:31:16.680 --> 00:31:17.470
Top three restaurants.

00:31:17.470 --> 00:31:19.360
That's so hard, but I'll try.

00:31:19.360 --> 00:31:22.820
One's closed, which is El Bulli,
which is Ferran Adria's

00:31:22.820 --> 00:31:24.490
restaurant in La Rosas.

00:31:24.490 --> 00:31:25.500
So that's not really fair.

00:31:25.500 --> 00:31:28.060
I'm not going to tell you how
great my 37, 5 and 1/2 hour

00:31:28.060 --> 00:31:30.920
course meal was because you
can't get there anymore.

00:31:30.920 --> 00:31:31.860
But it was.

00:31:31.860 --> 00:31:34.500
Thomas Keller, right here
at French Laundry.

00:31:34.500 --> 00:31:39.060
He's one of the best in the
world, not just the country.

00:31:39.060 --> 00:31:40.790
Much respect for him.

00:31:40.790 --> 00:31:42.520
Great friend, amazing chef.

00:31:42.520 --> 00:31:44.220
Just so freaking disciplined.

00:31:44.220 --> 00:31:46.430
You can walk-- and he does quite
often in his kitchen,

00:31:46.430 --> 00:31:48.210
walks around in white socks.

00:31:48.210 --> 00:31:49.260
No shoes.

00:31:49.260 --> 00:31:52.790
Because his kitchen floors
are that clean.

00:31:52.790 --> 00:31:53.870
Which is a Japanese mentality.

00:31:53.870 --> 00:31:56.890
When I worked in Japan, in
Osaka, we had rubber boots on.

00:31:56.890 --> 00:32:00.290
And we were hosing down
everything during service.

00:32:00.290 --> 00:32:02.620
It wasn't just afterwards.

00:32:02.620 --> 00:32:03.875
But I think Keller's
unbelievable.

00:32:07.930 --> 00:32:10.800
Best pastry chef in the
world is Pierre Herme.

00:32:10.800 --> 00:32:15.310
Pierre Herme, I got to work
with in Paris at Fauchon.

00:32:15.310 --> 00:32:17.216
He was the youngest executive
pastry chef

00:32:17.216 --> 00:32:20.020
ever at 28 at Fauchon.

00:32:20.020 --> 00:32:23.020
Just a big, jolly guy, although
serious as hell.

00:32:23.020 --> 00:32:28.300
And he had-- just to talk
about perfection--

00:32:28.300 --> 00:32:31.840
he had a box, huge box, next to
the "four," the oven, where

00:32:31.840 --> 00:32:33.890
he has five layers like
a gigantic pizza oven.

00:32:33.890 --> 00:32:37.020
We do all our croissants and
all these [INAUDIBLE]

00:32:37.020 --> 00:32:39.790
en pomme, the apple-filled ones,
and pan au chocolat, and

00:32:39.790 --> 00:32:40.440
things like that.

00:32:40.440 --> 00:32:42.820
They were twice the price at
Fauchon than any other

00:32:42.820 --> 00:32:43.990
boulangerie in Paris.

00:32:43.990 --> 00:32:46.550
So there were five francs
apiece rather than 2.50.

00:32:46.550 --> 00:32:49.120
We're talking 15,
18 years ago.

00:32:49.120 --> 00:32:51.790
And if it had a blemish--

00:32:51.790 --> 00:32:57.840
like a micron of croissant
skin off, in the box.

00:32:57.840 --> 00:33:00.150
And he had one rule-- eat
as much as anything you

00:33:00.150 --> 00:33:01.010
want, all the time.

00:33:01.010 --> 00:33:03.150
So when you first get there,
there's all these amazing

00:33:03.150 --> 00:33:04.580
Belgian chocolates,
croissants.

00:33:04.580 --> 00:33:06.230
And you just stuff you
face and after a week

00:33:06.230 --> 00:33:07.530
you don't eat anymore.

00:33:07.530 --> 00:33:09.910
It's like when you first get to
Google, you're like, oh my

00:33:09.910 --> 00:33:10.750
god, oh my god, oh my god.

00:33:10.750 --> 00:33:11.720
And you eat everything.

00:33:11.720 --> 00:33:12.970
And then it's like,
oh, lobster.

00:33:12.970 --> 00:33:15.270
Eh, veal.

00:33:15.270 --> 00:33:16.253
It's like Alaska-- eagle!

00:33:16.253 --> 00:33:16.596
Eagle!

00:33:16.596 --> 00:33:19.410
And then after three days,
you're like, eagle.

00:33:19.410 --> 00:33:19.620
Eagle.

00:33:19.620 --> 00:33:20.530
Oh, two eagles.

00:33:20.530 --> 00:33:21.980
You know.

00:33:21.980 --> 00:33:22.640
But PIerre--

00:33:22.640 --> 00:33:25.870
I have a funny story, Pierre.

00:33:25.870 --> 00:33:27.965
This was '86.

00:33:27.965 --> 00:33:28.810
And a lot of you--

00:33:28.810 --> 00:33:30.570
I don't know, some of
you weren't alive.

00:33:30.570 --> 00:33:34.040
So I got there like 5:30 in
the morning and he was

00:33:34.040 --> 00:33:37.150
sweating and swearing at his
[INAUDIBLE], which is a

00:33:37.150 --> 00:33:40.620
gigantic copper pot,
220 volts.

00:33:40.620 --> 00:33:44.730
And he was cooking this really
wet, nasty-looking stuff.

00:33:44.730 --> 00:33:46.900
I'm like-- and I speak
fluent French.

00:33:46.900 --> 00:33:48.910
I, you know, Pierre,
what are you doing?

00:33:48.910 --> 00:33:49.310
[FRENCH]

00:33:49.310 --> 00:33:51.545
And he's just swearing.

00:33:51.545 --> 00:33:54.360
I've never seen him
mad and swearing.

00:33:54.360 --> 00:33:57.460
He basically told me this was
fresh pumpkin and he was

00:33:57.460 --> 00:34:01.080
commissioned to make 20 pumpkin
pies at like $80 a

00:34:01.080 --> 00:34:04.280
pop, Fauchon style,
for Thanksgiving.

00:34:04.280 --> 00:34:06.840
So either some rich American
client or something wanted 20

00:34:06.840 --> 00:34:08.060
pumpkin pies.

00:34:08.060 --> 00:34:10.969
And if you've ever tried to cook
fresh pumpkin, it's just

00:34:10.969 --> 00:34:12.219
a watery mess.

00:34:12.219 --> 00:34:14.090
And you can never get
that great puree you

00:34:14.090 --> 00:34:15.770
get out of a can.

00:34:15.770 --> 00:34:17.489
So he's swearing and yelling.

00:34:17.489 --> 00:34:20.139
I'm like, Chef, I
can help you.

00:34:20.139 --> 00:34:22.639
And I was the lowest
out of 20 cooks.

00:34:22.639 --> 00:34:26.820
Basically, you know, what can
you, lowly cook, do for me?

00:34:26.820 --> 00:34:30.820
And I'm like, I can get you
cans of pumpkin puree.

00:34:30.820 --> 00:34:32.280
And he's like, "que?"

00:34:32.280 --> 00:34:34.570
Because my dad, again, he was
chief scientist, but he was at

00:34:34.570 --> 00:34:37.500
Wright-Patterson Air Force Base,
so civilian, so being a

00:34:37.500 --> 00:34:40.190
SES senior executive, brigadier
general level, he

00:34:40.190 --> 00:34:43.014
had access to the PX,
the US Embassy.

00:34:43.014 --> 00:34:45.730
I'm like, I can get you can.

00:34:45.730 --> 00:34:46.889
You want the cans or not?

00:34:46.889 --> 00:34:48.130
He goes, yeah, yeah.

00:34:48.130 --> 00:34:49.650
So I get to the embassy,
we call the

00:34:49.650 --> 00:34:50.610
people, they let me in.

00:34:50.610 --> 00:34:55.060
I bring two cases back of
Libby's pumpkin pie mix.

00:34:55.060 --> 00:34:57.480
And he opens them up and he's
like, ooh, [FRENCH].

00:34:57.480 --> 00:34:58.800
Because it's actually
really good, right?

00:34:58.800 --> 00:35:00.540
I mean, Libby's is the
best, in my opinion.

00:35:00.540 --> 00:35:02.340
It's got the little sweetness.

00:35:02.340 --> 00:35:03.580
It's got the cinnamon.

00:35:03.580 --> 00:35:05.480
And then he's like, [FRENCH]--

00:35:05.480 --> 00:35:06.000
what's the recipe?

00:35:06.000 --> 00:35:09.150
I'm like, recipe's right here.

00:35:09.150 --> 00:35:12.710
He made that recipe off of
Libby's can-- evaporated milk,

00:35:12.710 --> 00:35:14.230
sugar, this, eggs.

00:35:14.230 --> 00:35:16.820
Of course, his pastry crust
was awesome, pate sucree--

00:35:16.820 --> 00:35:17.215
delicious.

00:35:17.215 --> 00:35:18.730
It was actually the best
pumpkin pie I've

00:35:18.730 --> 00:35:20.450
ever had in my life.

00:35:20.450 --> 00:35:23.700
But here's the best pastry chef
in the world reading a

00:35:23.700 --> 00:35:25.080
Libby's can.

00:35:25.080 --> 00:35:25.880
[FRENCH]

00:35:25.880 --> 00:35:27.250
So fricking funny.

00:35:27.250 --> 00:35:28.380
True story.

00:35:28.380 --> 00:35:29.630
True story.

00:35:29.630 --> 00:35:32.195
And one of the moments I thought
I was going to be

00:35:32.195 --> 00:35:34.110
actually literally killed
by a chef--

00:35:34.110 --> 00:35:36.930
it never happened-- was also
Pierre Herme, obviously a

00:35:36.930 --> 00:35:39.200
great mentor of mine.

00:35:39.200 --> 00:35:43.510
But he also was famous
for blowing sugar.

00:35:43.510 --> 00:35:44.800
So I don't know if you know
about blowing sugar, but just

00:35:44.800 --> 00:35:47.290
like blowing glass, you get
sugar so fricking hot--

00:35:47.290 --> 00:35:49.100
I don't care who you are unless
you're Iron Man, it's

00:35:49.100 --> 00:35:49.880
so hard to touch.

00:35:49.880 --> 00:35:52.230
But you can make a ball, you
can take straw, whoosh, you

00:35:52.230 --> 00:35:54.870
can blow it and you can make
anything, just like glass.

00:35:54.870 --> 00:35:57.940
So he made-- and it took him
like a week and a half, which

00:35:57.940 --> 00:35:59.460
is a long time for him--

00:35:59.460 --> 00:36:00.850
made a Mickey Mouse.

00:36:00.850 --> 00:36:04.090
So this was when France was
trying to get Euro Disneyland.

00:36:04.090 --> 00:36:05.270
So there was a beaut--

00:36:05.270 --> 00:36:06.450
to the freaking T--

00:36:06.450 --> 00:36:09.390
black buttons, the ears,
the whole nine yards.

00:36:09.390 --> 00:36:11.980
Just to give him a photograph,
he can do it.

00:36:11.980 --> 00:36:14.370
Gigantic Mickey Mouse, right?

00:36:14.370 --> 00:36:15.620
And he was very proud of it.

00:36:15.620 --> 00:36:16.700
[INAUDIBLE] were like, oh, my
god, (WITH FRENCH ACCENT)

00:36:16.700 --> 00:36:17.750
Mickey, Mickey.

00:36:17.750 --> 00:36:19.580
That's Mickey in French.

00:36:19.580 --> 00:36:24.000
And he put it in the back room
to let it dry two days before

00:36:24.000 --> 00:36:26.160
it goes up into the room.

00:36:26.160 --> 00:36:27.370
So this is where all
the freezers were.

00:36:27.370 --> 00:36:28.735
Yeah, uh-oh.

00:36:28.735 --> 00:36:31.790
And so I'm back there and
I don't know what--

00:36:31.790 --> 00:36:33.760
you know, sometimes you
just do things and

00:36:33.760 --> 00:36:35.660
you're like, WTF--

00:36:35.660 --> 00:36:39.820
that's "where's the food,"
by the way, just in case.

00:36:39.820 --> 00:36:42.570
I said, god, I wanted
to touch his belly.

00:36:42.570 --> 00:36:45.456
So I touched his belly.

00:36:45.456 --> 00:36:48.980
And just like in "Animal House,"
right, when John

00:36:48.980 --> 00:36:50.655
Belushi's like, whoa, a--

00:36:50.655 --> 00:36:53.860
my fingerprint of my
thumb ended up

00:36:53.860 --> 00:36:56.280
right on Mickey's belly.

00:36:56.280 --> 00:36:57.480
I'm like, holy sh--

00:36:57.480 --> 00:37:00.110
I'm looking around, make
sure no one saw me.

00:37:00.110 --> 00:37:03.890
I mean, he would have killed me,
a week and a half of work.

00:37:03.890 --> 00:37:07.750
And I just scurried away.

00:37:07.750 --> 00:37:11.560
And for the next three or four
days, I woke up every night

00:37:11.560 --> 00:37:14.140
screaming and sweating
and crying.

00:37:14.140 --> 00:37:17.160
And the dream nightmare was
he's lining us all up.

00:37:17.160 --> 00:37:17.990
Let me see your thumb.

00:37:17.990 --> 00:37:19.370
And they're like this.

00:37:19.370 --> 00:37:21.910
I literally thought, should I
burn my thumbs and then, oh,

00:37:21.910 --> 00:37:23.070
[FRENCH], Chef.

00:37:23.070 --> 00:37:24.153
I was like, cut my thumbs off.

00:37:24.153 --> 00:37:25.230
I didn't know what I--

00:37:25.230 --> 00:37:27.470
and then, fortunately it got
into the window and then you

00:37:27.470 --> 00:37:28.650
never saw it again.

00:37:28.650 --> 00:37:31.160
And you can't patch it.

00:37:31.160 --> 00:37:33.860
The color's in the glass, in
the sugar, so you couldn't

00:37:33.860 --> 00:37:34.830
have painted over it.

00:37:34.830 --> 00:37:37.960
I mean, I was just so SOL,
but he never saw it.

00:37:37.960 --> 00:37:41.180
So hopefully he doesn't
see this video either.

00:37:41.180 --> 00:37:42.460
Thanks, [CHINESE].

00:37:42.460 --> 00:37:44.940
Nice to see you.

00:37:44.940 --> 00:37:46.970
All right, sir.

00:37:46.970 --> 00:37:48.820
Oh, you know, let me answer--

00:37:48.820 --> 00:37:49.580
continue--

00:37:49.580 --> 00:37:54.020
one Japanese restaurant,
Nobu Matsuhisa.

00:37:54.020 --> 00:37:56.450
Matsuhisa, in LA, which
I just was again.

00:37:56.450 --> 00:37:58.250
His original, I think,
is phenomenal.

00:37:58.250 --> 00:38:01.430
If money is of no object and
Larry's taking you out to

00:38:01.430 --> 00:38:06.690
dinner, go to Masa in New York
City, where its $400 a person

00:38:06.690 --> 00:38:08.680
for omikase, before sake.

00:38:08.680 --> 00:38:12.270
You'll drop $800, $1,000 each.

00:38:12.270 --> 00:38:13.710
So you really need Larry.

00:38:13.710 --> 00:38:14.710
Seriously.

00:38:14.710 --> 00:38:18.810
But it's pristine
sushi, sashami.

00:38:18.810 --> 00:38:21.910
It's uni risotto with white
shaved truffles.

00:38:21.910 --> 00:38:24.950
It's foie gras shabu shabu,
which I know you can't have

00:38:24.950 --> 00:38:26.160
here anymore.

00:38:26.160 --> 00:38:28.566
And best Chinese is hard.

00:38:28.566 --> 00:38:29.830
It's so hard.

00:38:33.100 --> 00:38:35.710
Best dim sum, I think, in San
Francisco, is a small place

00:38:35.710 --> 00:38:39.000
called Ton Kiang, T-O-N
K-I-A-N-G. It's

00:38:39.000 --> 00:38:41.540
Geary and 21st Avenue.

00:38:41.540 --> 00:38:44.100
Ton Kiang, fantastic dim sum.

00:38:44.100 --> 00:38:45.530
Wu Kong is fantastic.

00:38:45.530 --> 00:38:46.860
Yong Sing is fantastic
downtown.

00:38:46.860 --> 00:38:49.420
But Ton Kiang in the avenues.

00:38:49.420 --> 00:38:51.020
Clement Street's the new
Chinatown, right?

00:38:51.020 --> 00:38:52.520
We lived up in the avenues.

00:38:52.520 --> 00:38:54.970
And note this, though.

00:38:54.970 --> 00:38:58.080
A block more north, on 22nd
between 22nd and 23rd is a

00:38:58.080 --> 00:39:01.700
great place called Tommy's, the
best margarita you'll ever

00:39:01.700 --> 00:39:02.760
have in your life.

00:39:02.760 --> 00:39:04.100
I'll be there tonight.

00:39:04.100 --> 00:39:06.340
Because actually, if you're in
San Francisco, come to see the

00:39:06.340 --> 00:39:07.260
squash tournament.

00:39:07.260 --> 00:39:10.240
There's a huge squash tournament
down there in--

00:39:10.240 --> 00:39:11.410
Embarcadero, is it?

00:39:11.410 --> 00:39:12.550
Something like that.

00:39:12.550 --> 00:39:14.570
Outdoor squash, the best squash
players in the world.

00:39:14.570 --> 00:39:16.420
Anyway, and I'm a
big squasher.

00:39:16.420 --> 00:39:18.320
And again, my brother-in-law's
a coach at Stanford.

00:39:18.320 --> 00:39:19.890
So we're all going to
Tommy's tonight.

00:39:19.890 --> 00:39:23.790
But the bartenders have arms
like this, because they

00:39:23.790 --> 00:39:26.690
squeeze every lime to order
for every margarita.

00:39:26.690 --> 00:39:28.640
So anyway.

00:39:28.640 --> 00:39:30.020
I could go on and on and on.

00:39:30.020 --> 00:39:30.970
But those are good.

00:39:30.970 --> 00:39:33.730
Robichoun, of course,
fantastic in France.

00:39:33.730 --> 00:39:35.360
But those are the tops.

00:39:35.360 --> 00:39:37.010
Last 20 years, what's
happened to food?

00:39:39.880 --> 00:39:43.360
A lot and nothing, which
is good and bad.

00:39:43.360 --> 00:39:48.440
There was this whole molecular
gastronomy the last 15 years--

00:39:48.440 --> 00:39:51.090
exploding this and
all of that.

00:39:51.090 --> 00:39:52.860
And liquid nitrogen.

00:39:52.860 --> 00:39:55.760
And if you can do it
well, it's genius.

00:39:55.760 --> 00:39:59.650
So Ferran Adria, Jose Andres.

00:39:59.650 --> 00:40:03.520
So Jose Andres at Minibar in
DC, is literally an 8-seat

00:40:03.520 --> 00:40:04.350
kind of sushi bar.

00:40:04.350 --> 00:40:06.320
And there you can get
a fantastic meal.

00:40:06.320 --> 00:40:09.010
It's impossible to get a
reservation, but you can

00:40:09.010 --> 00:40:10.550
Google it somehow.

00:40:10.550 --> 00:40:11.370
Closed Saturdays.

00:40:11.370 --> 00:40:12.620
No, just kidding.

00:40:14.520 --> 00:40:18.840
And there's a guy named Grant
Achatz in Chicago, Alinea.

00:40:18.840 --> 00:40:20.490
Genius.

00:40:20.490 --> 00:40:23.110
So when you do it right, it's
really the most amazing,

00:40:23.110 --> 00:40:25.090
extraordinary dining
experience ever.

00:40:25.090 --> 00:40:28.990
But when you do it wrong,
it's stupid.

00:40:28.990 --> 00:40:30.630
Bubble gum taco?

00:40:30.630 --> 00:40:31.360
why?

00:40:31.360 --> 00:40:33.240
Why would you do a
bubble gum taco?

00:40:33.240 --> 00:40:34.490
There's no reason to.

00:40:37.050 --> 00:40:38.210
And I can't do it.

00:40:38.210 --> 00:40:42.550
I mean, I'll do pineapple
caviar, because you can use

00:40:42.550 --> 00:40:44.240
things that-- but that's
for dessert.

00:40:44.240 --> 00:40:46.880
But it's not my forte at all.

00:40:46.880 --> 00:40:48.620
It takes an army of people.

00:40:48.620 --> 00:40:50.910
And then when you do it well,
you charge a fortune because

00:40:50.910 --> 00:40:51.980
you have an army of people.

00:40:51.980 --> 00:40:57.240
But Alinea right now, is
probably the best of all the

00:40:57.240 --> 00:40:59.130
places that do it
in the world.

00:40:59.130 --> 00:41:06.090
There is Noma, in Copenhagen,
who's rated

00:41:06.090 --> 00:41:06.900
best chef in the world.

00:41:06.900 --> 00:41:07.790
He does.

00:41:07.790 --> 00:41:09.120
Rene Redzepi does a
little bit too.

00:41:09.120 --> 00:41:09.960
I've never been there.

00:41:09.960 --> 00:41:11.210
It's too far.

00:41:14.970 --> 00:41:17.290
The whole local movement--

00:41:17.290 --> 00:41:20.330
you being Californians are the
strongest, which is great,

00:41:20.330 --> 00:41:22.560
because you have a 12-month
growing season, so you can

00:41:22.560 --> 00:41:23.800
actually do it.

00:41:23.800 --> 00:41:28.640
But sourcing locally, using
all the local, fishing

00:41:28.640 --> 00:41:32.660
sustainably, that's always
been the way in

00:41:32.660 --> 00:41:34.100
Europe, to be honest.

00:41:34.100 --> 00:41:37.110
We just went away with it
because we discovered canning

00:41:37.110 --> 00:41:38.690
and preservation.

00:41:38.690 --> 00:41:40.520
And freezing.

00:41:40.520 --> 00:41:44.420
So when America discovered that
in the mid-1900s, that

00:41:44.420 --> 00:41:45.570
kind of ruined everything.

00:41:45.570 --> 00:41:49.740
Because up until 90 years ago,
it used to be all your food

00:41:49.740 --> 00:41:54.060
came within 100 miles to
your house, period.

00:41:54.060 --> 00:41:56.840
But then once you brought in
frozen TV dinners and canning,

00:41:56.840 --> 00:41:58.820
Campbell's soup and this, then
you could get it from

00:41:58.820 --> 00:41:59.830
everywhere.

00:41:59.830 --> 00:42:02.200
So thankfully people
are realizing--

00:42:02.200 --> 00:42:05.030
and we have a four or five
month growing season.

00:42:05.030 --> 00:42:07.190
And there's lots of tubers and
stuff in the winter as well.

00:42:07.190 --> 00:42:10.710
So even in Boston, we can
do as much as we can.

00:42:10.710 --> 00:42:11.610
I'm a huge--

00:42:11.610 --> 00:42:14.640
look, if you get organic
local, that's the best.

00:42:14.640 --> 00:42:17.750
But an organic tomato from
California or from Napa

00:42:17.750 --> 00:42:20.630
delivered to Boston versus a
local tomato that I can get in

00:42:20.630 --> 00:42:22.655
Lexington, local is better.

00:42:22.655 --> 00:42:26.250
One, it tastes better, because
you lose so much nutrient

00:42:26.250 --> 00:42:29.300
balance and flavor in
the air coming over.

00:42:29.300 --> 00:42:32.210
Two, it's so much better for the
world because you're not

00:42:32.210 --> 00:42:32.870
taking gas.

00:42:32.870 --> 00:42:35.590
I mean, I used to serve
Fiji water.

00:42:35.590 --> 00:42:36.400
That's stupid.

00:42:36.400 --> 00:42:37.990
Water from Fiji?

00:42:37.990 --> 00:42:40.430
The amount of energy and waste
it takes to bring water from

00:42:40.430 --> 00:42:42.260
Fiji when I have water
right here--

00:42:42.260 --> 00:42:44.220
they have these great systems
that you guys have.

00:42:44.220 --> 00:42:46.480
Use your tap water
and filter it.

00:42:46.480 --> 00:42:48.140
Add bubbles.

00:42:48.140 --> 00:42:50.705
So I think that movement is here
to stay because people

00:42:50.705 --> 00:42:54.330
are realizing it's
just smarter.

00:42:54.330 --> 00:42:57.660
And combination because of
recession and times are

00:42:57.660 --> 00:43:02.380
tighter and family structure
is the topic of every

00:43:02.380 --> 00:43:04.060
conversation, regardless of
whether it's the political

00:43:04.060 --> 00:43:08.380
season, but it always is, is
dining family and cooking more

00:43:08.380 --> 00:43:08.885
family style.

00:43:08.885 --> 00:43:13.190
And cooking more simple food,
which is a lot like this book.

00:43:13.190 --> 00:43:16.420
I do not try to be a fancy
fine-dining chef at all in the

00:43:16.420 --> 00:43:19.340
cookbook, because who wants
to cook that way?

00:43:19.340 --> 00:43:22.250
It's really more about how can
you entertain, how can you

00:43:22.250 --> 00:43:24.060
make great, tasty
food cheaply?

00:43:24.060 --> 00:43:28.120
Most of these dishes are $20
or less for four people.

